{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015Az72mWeBey7hh23o76ZPw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the KEY-QUESTIONS framework.\n\n**Behavior 1**: The traveling-salesman heuristic produces a route that is no more than 1.5x the length of the optimal route for inputs up to 20 stops.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is testing the TSP heuristic algorithm itself - one function/module's logic. No module boundary interaction needed.\n- REAL-INFRA: No OS/network/subprocess needed.\n- MOCK-HIDE: The heuristic is a pure algorithm - no dependencies to mock.\n- LLM-DEP: No LLM involved.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No.\n\nThis is a unit test - I can test the heuristic function directly with known coordinates and verify the route length stays within the 1.5x bound.\n\n**Behavior 2**: Delivery time window estimates computed correctly from distance and configured average speed.\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is computing time windows from distance and speed - pure calculation logic. One function's math.\n- REAL-INFRA: No.\n- MOCK-HIDE: No real dependencies needed.\n- LLM-DEP: No.\n\nUnit test - pure calculation.\n\n**Behavior 3**: Shift-hours validator rejects route exce\n\neding driver's remaining shift hours. This is validation logic - one function checking total time vs shift hours, returning excess. Unit test - pure validation logic.\n\n**Behavior 4**: When one address fails geocoding (API returns no results), service skips that stop and optimizes remaining addresses, reporting which were skipped. This is an integration point between geocoding and route optimization - I need to verify that when geocoding fails, the system correctly skips the address and reports it. I can mock the geocoding API to return no results for a specific address.\n\nThe real question is whether mocking the geocoding layer would hide a genuine failure in how the pipeline handles missing results across module boundaries. The failure mode I'm testing is whether the system properly skips and reports when geocoding returns nothing - that's fundamentally about the integration between geocoding response handling and the optimizer/reporter working together.\n\nFor Behavior 5, I'm trying to determine if deduplication and consolidation of addresses with combined delivery items is a single module responsibility or requires interaction across multiple modules. If it's purely input normalization before geocoding and optimization, it could be Unit level, but if combining delivery items needs to coordinate with the optimizer's input preparation, that pushes it to Integration.\n\nLooking at my final assessment: Behaviors 1-3 and 5 are Unit tests (algorithm quality, math, validation, and input normalization), while Behavior 4 is Integration because the skip-and-optimize flow requires the geocoding module to fail, the service to detect and filter that failure, the optimizer to run on the remaining addresses, and the reporting module to capture what was skipped—that's clearly multiple modules interacting. the consolidation function can be tested in isolation—if it correctly merges duplicate addresses into a single stop with combined items, that's a Unit test. The optimizer receiving only one entry follows naturally from that, so I don't need Integration coverage here.\n\nMy final assessments are: TSP heuristic quality as Unit (pure algorithm), time window calculation as Unit (pure math), shift validator as Unit (pure logic), geocoding failure through skip to optimize to report as Integration (spans multiple modules), and deduplication as Unit (input normalization).\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions for each behavior, starting with the TSP heuristic—mostly Unit since it's algorithm testing, though there's a small chance it could be Integration if the coordinate system integration matters.\n\nFor time window calculation, this is clearly Unit—straightforward mathematical logic. The shift validator is equally clear-cut Unit. The geocoding failure scenario is definitely Integration, with some System probability if they're testing against a real API. For deduplication, it's predominantly Unit with a modest chance of Integration if they want to verify the full pipeline behavior.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9473,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9473},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0301af2d-bc35-4600-aefc-ae9629ea114c","uuid":"90442a07-b709-485a-9298-314977c68326"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015Az72mWeBey7hh23o76ZPw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01UpRBUi9m7m56uzZyMWdZiD","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"TSP heuristic produces a route no more than 1.5x optimal for up to 20 stops","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is purely algorithmic — the heuristic function either finds a good-enough route or it doesn't. No module boundary is crossed; the function takes coordinates and returns an ordered route. REAL-INFRA: None needed. MOCK-HIDE: No dependencies to mock — coordinates are pure data. LLM-DEP: No. The test needs a set of known coordinates with a computable optimal route length (e.g., small grid) and compares the heuristic output against the 1.5x bound.","test_description":"Construct a fixed set of ≤20 coordinate pairs for which the optimal route length is known (e.g., a convex polygon or a brute-force-computed baseline). Call the TSP heuristic function directly with those coordinates. Assert that the returned route's total Euclidean distance is ≤ 1.5× the optimal. Also verify the returned route visits every stop exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Delivery time window estimates are computed correctly from distance and configured average speed per road type","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: This is arithmetic — time = distance / speed. The failure mode lives entirely within a single calculation function. There is no module boundary: the function receives distance and a road-type-keyed speed config and returns time windows. REAL-INFRA: None. MOCK-HIDE: No dependency to mock; speed config is a plain dict. LLM-DEP: No. A unit test with fixed inputs fully covers this behavior.","test_description":"Call the time-window estimation function directly with a table of (distance, road_type, speed_config) inputs and assert the returned window matches the expected value (distance / speed). Cover multiple road types (e.g., highway vs. urban) to verify the config lookup is correct. Include an edge case where distance is 0 (stop at the same location).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Shift-hours validator rejects a route whose total estimated time exceeds the driver's remaining shift hours, returning the excess amount","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The validator receives a total-estimated-time value and a remaining-shift-hours value and makes a binary accept/reject decision while computing excess. This is a single function's logic — no handoff to another module is involved in the failure mode. REAL-INFRA: None. MOCK-HIDE: No dependency exists to mock. LLM-DEP: No. A unit test drives all branches (exactly at limit, over limit, under limit).","test_description":"Call the shift validator function directly with (total_time, remaining_shift) pairs covering: total_time < remaining_shift (accepted, no excess), total_time == remaining_shift (boundary — accepted with 0 excess), and total_time > remaining_shift (rejected, excess = total_time - remaining_shift). Assert the return value for each case matches the expected outcome and excess amount.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.92,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When one address fails geocoding, the service skips that stop, optimizes remaining addresses, and reports which addresses were skipped","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode is a cross-module handoff: the geocoding layer signals a no-results result, the orchestration layer must detect it, remove the stop from the candidate list before passing it to the optimizer, and accumulate the skipped address in a separate report. A unit test on any single module cannot catch a bug where, say, the failed address silently falls through to the optimizer or disappears from the skipped-addresses list. The failure only surfaces when the geocoding adapter, the filtering/orchestration logic, the optimizer input builder, and the skip-reporting path all interact. REAL-INFRA: Geocoding API is external HTTP, but it can be stubbed at the HTTP client or adapter layer. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the geocoding call at the right adapter boundary exposes the orchestration bug without hiding it. LLM-DEP: No.","test_description":"Wire the full service pipeline (geocoding adapter, optimizer, skip reporter) with the geocoding HTTP client replaced by a stub that returns a no-results response for exactly one address and valid coordinates for all others. Invoke the service with a list of N addresses (one of which is the failing one). Assert: (a) the optimizer is called with N-1 stops (not N), (b) the returned route contains no stop for the failing address, (c) the response's skipped-addresses field lists the failing address exactly once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Duplicate addresses are consolidated into a single stop with combined delivery items, not visited twice","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Deduplication and item-consolidation is a self-contained preprocessing step on the input list. The failure mode — producing two stops instead of one, or losing delivery items during merge — lives in the consolidation function itself. The optimizer is only ever handed the deduplicated list; if consolidation is correct, the optimizer visiting the stop once follows trivially. REAL-INFRA: None. MOCK-HIDE: No dependency to mock. LLM-DEP: No. A unit test on the consolidation function with a crafted input list fully covers this behavior.","test_description":"Call the address-consolidation function with an input list containing two entries for the same address, each with distinct delivery items. Assert: (a) the output contains exactly one stop for that address, (b) the stop's delivery-items collection is the union of both input entries' items, (c) all other addresses in the list remain unaffected. Also test that three or more duplicates collapse to one stop with all items merged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9473,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9473},"output_tokens":6,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"0301af2d-bc35-4600-aefc-ae9629ea114c","uuid":"58df1618-1bb3-4015-9f30-7cac737f27a3"}
